stimulus: Welcome to the experiment. Press any key to begin.

This is Mr. Frog!

He speaks a different language and needs help finding the items he wants. Can you help Mr. Frog?

Press any key to move to the next page.

In each trial, you will be shown an image that will be labeled with a word in the language that Mr. Frog speaks.

Your job will be to select all the items that you think matches what Mr. Frog is asking for.

Press any key to begin.

Here is a wug. Can you give Mr. Frog all the other wugs?

Click on all of the wugs below. If you change your mind, you can unselect any image.

Click the Submit button when you are done selecting all the wugs.

Debrief: In this experiment, we wanted to see how people learn subordinate word meanings (e.g., “dalmatian”) when

superordinate (e.g., “animal”) and basic-level (e.g., “dog”) meanings can also be reasonable label referents.

We thought that when presented with three subordinate exemplars (aka the trials with three images), a word will be generalized

to the subordinate level more often than when presented with one subordinate exemplar (aka the trials with one image).
